Photo by Tim Gouw on UnsplashBuilding a countdown timer in React sounds like a very basic, beginner-level task. You set up a state variable, declare a setInterval inside a useEffect, and……done!
But if you try to write it the way you would in vanilla JavaScript, you run into something very odd. The timer ticks down exactly once — say, from 10 to 9 — and then just stays there. The code doesn’t crash, there are no errors in the console, but the UI completely remains still.
If you console.log the state inside the interval, it will print 9 again and again.
This isn’t a React bug. This is what is called a ‘stale closure’, which is the inner function referencing to the “stale” or outdated values of its outer lexical scope even after those values have been updated. This certainly catches almost every developer moving from vanilla JS to React.

The Code That Makes the Time Stop
Most people run into this when they try to build something like a quiz countdown or a pomodoro clock. The instinct is to set up the interval once when the component mounts, so you leave the dependency array empty:
const [seconds, setSeconds] = useState(10);useEffect(() => {
const interval = setInterval(() => {
// Read the current seconds and subtract 1
setSeconds(seconds - 1);
}, 1000);
return () => clearInterval(interval);
}, []); // Only run once on mount
This logic looks fine. You even added the cleanup function to clear the interval when the component unmounts. But by leaving the dependency array empty, the timer gets stuck in a loop.
NOTE : The cleanup function inside useEffect runs right before the start of the second execution (and before every subsequent execution). It does not run immediately after the first execution finishes
How Closures Handle State Snapshots
To understand why this happens, you have to look at how JavaScript functions handle variables outside of them. This is called a closure.
When your component first renders, the seconds variable is 10. The useEffect is executed, and the setInterval function is created. As it is initialized, it looks at its surrounding state and captures a snapshot of the variables it needs. In its memory, it records: seconds is equal to 10.
Because the dependency array at the bottom is completely empty [], you told React to never re-run this effect. That means this specific interval function never gets recreated. It runs forever in the background with that initial snapshot.

